tool.name: VegFrax_Fractional_Cover

param.name: in_low_nc
param.dialogReference: A raw satellite data NetCDF generated by the COG Fetch module. Input NetCDF must have coordinates for x, y and time.

param.name: in_high_tif
param.dialogReference:
A GeoTiff raster layer representing a high-resolution, pre-classified landscape or vegetation types. These are typically produced from World-View image classification procedures or from rasterised vegetation vectors.

Note: this layer must be in the GeoTiff format (.tif), projected in the GDA94 Albers projection (EPSG: 3577), and must be of data type Integer (e.g., int16, int32, int64).

param.name: out_nc_file
param.dialogReference: The NetCDF file containing the fractional cover map output. This output will always contain x, y coordinates as well as a seperate variable representing one or more of the requested class values.

param.name: in_aggregate_dates
param.dialogReference:
Combine all data within the input satellite NetCDF when performing analysis. This is recommended to reduce inter-annual seasonal fluctuation.

If not selected, choose a specific year to threshold.

param.name: in_start_date
param.dialogReference:
The start date in the satellite NetCDF to subset to for consideration in fractional cover analysis. All satellite data prior to this date will be excluded.

The default value is the first date detected in the input NetCDF.

param.name: in_end_date
param.dialogReference:
The end date in the satellite NetCDF to subset to for consideration in fractional cover analysis. All satellite data following this date will be excluded.

The default value is the last date detected in the input NetCDF.

param.name: in_classes
param.dialogReference:
The class (or classes) contained with the high resolution GeoTIFF that will be considered during fractional cover analysis. Each class is analysed separately.

Note: due to the requirement to analyse classes separately, outputs generally will not add up perfectly to 1.

param.name: in_aggregate_classes
param.dialogReference: Sum all fractional values in the selected classes on output to create a singular combined fractional map. This is useful if several classes are similar in spectral characterstics and are easier represented as a single class.

param.name: in_num_samples
param.dialogReference:
The number of stratified random samples generated to train the random forest regression model. Each class within the GeoTiff will have this number of randomly sampled training points generated for it (if possible).

Note: at least 100 samples per class are recommended. An error may occur if random samples did not capture a class, so ensure that there is a sufficient number of pixels per class.

param.name: in_max_nodata
param.dialogReference:
NoData values may be introduced into the regressor when lower-resolution pixel "windows" are generated at the edge of a classified GeoTiff. To combat this, any window with NoData values within exclude the NoData value fraction and normalise the other classes from 0 to 1 and the window is then flagged as problematic.

This parameter allows some control over the fraction of NoData within a window that may be included in analysis. If only non-NoData windows are required, set to 0. If windows with 10% NoData values is ok, set to 0.1.

param.name: in_smooth
param.dialogReference: Some fractional cover outputs may look "noisy" in areas if the regressor struggles to distinguish between certain classes. Use this option to apply a median filter to the outputs to reduce noise.

param.name: in_num_estimators
param.dialogReference:
The number of trees in the random forest. Typically a higher value results in a more trustworthy model at the expensive of considerably longer processing time.

Note: the recommended default is 100. Start at 100 and increase to 500, 1000, etc.

See for more details: https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/generated/sklearn.ensemble.RandomForestRegressor.

param.name: in_criterion
param.expression: Mean Squared Error | Mean Absolute Error | Poisson
param.dialogReference:
Supported criteria are “squared_error” for the mean squared error, which is equal to variance reduction as feature selection criterion, “absolute_error” for the mean absolute error, and “poisson” which uses reduction in Poisson deviance to find splits.

Note: Mean Squared Error is the recommended criterion.

See for more details: https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/generated/sklearn.ensemble.RandomForestRegressor.

param.name: in_max_depth
param.dialogReference:
The maximum depth of the tree. Leaving this empty ensures that nodes are expanded until all leaves are pure or until all leaves contain less than 1 sample.

Note: Leaving this empty is recommended.

See for more details: https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/generated/sklearn.ensemble.RandomForestRegressor.

param.name: in_max_features
param.dialogReference:
The number of features to consider when looking for the best split. Two options are provided:

- Auto: maximum number of features is the square root of total number of features

- Log2: maximum number of features is the binary log of total number of features

Note: Auto is recommended.

See for more details: https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/generated/sklearn.ensemble.RandomForestRegressor.

param.name: in_boostrap
param.dialogReference:
Whether bootstrap samples are used when building trees. If False, the whole dataset is used to build each tree.

Note: Bootstrapping is recommended.

See for more details: https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/generated/sklearn.ensemble.RandomForestRegressor.

param.name: in_fmask_flags
param.expression: NoData | Valid | Cloud | Shadow | Snow | Water
param.dialogReference:
Pixel classes provided by the DEA Fmask algorithm. The DEA Landsat and Sentinel satellite image products come with a mask band to assist in removing clouds, shadow, nodata, etc. Only selected pixel classes shown here will be used in analysis, whilst all others will be masked out.

The default values include Valid, Snow and Water classes, and all others are masked out.

param.name: in_max_cloud
param.dialogReference:
The maximum percentage of cloud cover allowed within a satellite image before it is discarded from analysis. A value of 0 will return all satellite data with no registered cloud cover.

As a general rule of thumb, the smaller your study area the lower this value should be. The default value is 10%.

param.name: in_add_result_to_map
param.dialogReference: Whether to visualise the outputs of the tool on the currently active map.

tool.summary:
VegFrax combines high-resolution, classified imagery (e.g., classified World-View) and lower-resolution Landsat/Sentinel imagery to create fractional cover maps. The benefit of this method is that classes represented on the high-resolution image can be extrapolated to a much wider landscape extent via the lower-resolution data and random forest regression. Fractional maps are generated for all (or selected) classes of the high-resolution image.

Technically, VegFrax extracts pixel values in a high resolution classified image that fall within randomly selected lower-resolution pixels and determines the proportion of all classes within. These proportions are then used to train the regressor and predict onto unexplored pixels. As an example, if a high-resolution raster has a pixel size of 1m and the lower-resolution image has a pixel size of 10m, each random sample will have a window that captures 100 1m class pixels within - the percentage of each class in that window is calculated. For example, 25 forest pixels would = 25% forest.

See citation: Khare, S., Latifi, H., Rossi, S. and Ghosh, S.K., 2019. Fractional cover mapping of invasive plant species by combining very high-resolution stereo and multi-sensor multispectral imageries. Forests, 10(7), p.540.
